    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-02-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-02-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="120"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d120">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 774/23–27.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Minister
                            <persName type="to">Rockhill</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,<date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-02-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 23, 1907</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 256.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    interesting dispatch No. 497, of the 4th ultimo, on the subject of the
                    suppression of the opium trade in China.</p>
                <p>The department approves your statement to the Wai-wu Pu, that before asking the
                    United States to agree to the immediate enforcement of the provisions of the
                    treaty of October 8, 1903, China should herself do all she is required to do
                    under Article XVI of the treaty.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Elihu Root.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
